{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01XRNM2arcZEx67D3fHVszJ9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"No openssl-toolbox pod exists yet. The problem description says one is \"available for certificate generation.\" I need to create it or use a different approach.\n\nActually, looking at the problem statement again: \"An openssl-toolbox pod is available for certificate generation.\" This might mean I need to create one.\n\nActually, CockroachDB has its own `cockroach cert` subcommand which can be used for generating certificates. Alternatively, I can use `openssl` in the crdb-cluster-0 pod itself if available, or create an openssl-toolbox pod, or use cockroach's built-in cert generation.\nThe CockroachDB image should have the `cockroach cert` command built-in, so I can use that to generate the CA certificate, node certificates, and client certificates, then store them in Kubernetes secrets and update the StatefulSet to use TLS. Kubernetes secrets from these certs, then update the StatefulSet to mount them and switch from `--insecure` to `--certs-dir`. I think the cleanest approach is to use `kubectl run` with the CockroachDB image to generate the certs, or exec into an existing pod to create them there, then copy the generated files out to the host and create secrets from them.\n\nI'll exec into crdb-cluster-0 to generate the CA and node certificates for all the cluster endpoints, then copy those cert files out locally...\n\nCreating Kubernetes secrets... I could consolidate all the certificates into a single secret since they're all mounted to the same directory in the pod. But I need to reconsider the health check configuration too, since switching to HTTPS means updating the probe settings from HTTP to the secure endpoint.\n\nLooking at the StatefulSet changes needed: I'll swap out the `--insecure` flag for `--certs-dir=/cockroach/cockroach-certs`, add the volume mount and secret volume, and update those probes to use HTTPS. The trickier part is making sure the node certificates are valid for all the hostnames the nodes might be accessed through—localhost, the pod IP, and the full FQDN like `crdb-cluster-N.crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local`.\n\nI can generate a single shared node cert that covers all these patterns since they're consistent across the cluster. But I need to be careful about file permissions—CockroachDB is strict about requiring 0600 for key files and 0644 for cert files, and Kubernetes secrets mounted as volumes might not have the right permissions by default.\n\nI'll set `defaultMode: 0400` in the volume spec to ensure the mounted files have the correct restrictive permissions that CockroachDB expects. Now let me work through the implementation step by step.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":491,"cache_read_input_tokens":31104,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":491},"output_tokens":23,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c3ce2be6-5b8e-4bb8-978f-c7c755f9b167","uuid":"162ce1c1-30c0-47b2-8570-5a93e9ad9eb6","request_id":"req_011Ccb6LAXwGGAoF8wNLsGq9"}
